# Biceps Femoris

> The **biceps femoris** is the lateral hamstring muscle with two heads. It is the primary lateral knee flexor and a key hip extensor, inserting on the [[Fibular Head]].

## 🔗 Key Connections
- **Long head origin** — [[Ischial Tuberosity]] of [[Hip Bone]]
- **Short head origin** — [[Linea Aspera]] (lateral lip) of [[Femur]]
- **Insertion** — [[Fibular Head]] (and lateral [[Tibia]])
- **Nerve** — Long head: [[Sciatic Nerve]] (tibial division, L5–S2); Short head: sciatic (fibular division, L5–S1)
- **Action** — Knee flexion + lateral rotation; hip extension (long head)

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Hamstring strain** — Most common at the musculotendinous junction; sprinting injury
- **Common fibular nerve** — Runs just posterior to the biceps femoris tendon at the knee → at risk in knee dislocations

